    <h1>About this calculator</h1>
    <p>
      This site helps homeowners ballpark a generator size using a simplified interpretation of the
      National Electrical Code (NEC) dwelling load method, tailored for <strong>residential optional standby systems</strong>.
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">How the calculator works</h2>
    <ul style="padding-left:1.25rem; margin: .5rem 0;">
      <li><strong>Square‑footage general load:</strong> <code>3&nbsp;VA/ft²</code> based on the area you enter (NEC&nbsp;2023 approach includes garage &amp; basement).</li>
      <li><strong>Required small‑appliance &amp; laundry circuits:</strong> <code>1,500&nbsp;VA</code> each × quantity.</li>
      <li><strong>Fixed appliances:</strong> user‑selected nameplate running watts at <strong>100%</strong> (well, sump, dishwasher, range, etc.).</li>
      <li><strong>Demand factor:</strong> apply <strong>first 10&nbsp;kVA at 100%</strong>, then <strong>the remainder at 40%</strong> to the non‑A/C portion.</li>
      <li><strong>Seasonal maximum (heating vs cooling):</strong> add <strong>100% of the larger</strong> of A/C or heating. For heat pumps with electric supplemental heat we add the A/C run plus <strong>65%</strong> of supplemental kW.</li>
      <li><strong>EV charging (Level 2):</strong> added at <strong>100%</strong> based on selected amperage (32/40/48/60/80A @240V) or a custom kW.</li>
      <li><strong>Headroom buffer:</strong> default <strong>20%</strong>. We divide by <code>(1 − buffer)</code> and round up to the next common generator size (10/14/18/22/24/26&nbsp;kW air‑cooled).</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="color:#666; margin-top:.5rem;">
      Assumptions reflect typical residential equipment and are updated periodically. Always verify against nameplates and local code amendments.
    </p>
  </section>

    <section style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">What this site is (and isn’t)</h2>
    <p>
      This tool is oriented to <strong>residential optional standby systems</strong> (NEC Article&nbsp;702). It is <em>not</em> intended for
      <strong>emergency systems</strong> (Article&nbsp;700), <strong>legally required standby</strong> (Article&nbsp;701), or
      <strong>critical operations power systems</strong> (Article&nbsp;708), which have different design, reliability, and code requirements.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is <strong>planning guidance</strong>, not a site survey. Homes vary, nameplates can surprise, and local AHJs may amend the NEC.
      Before purchasing or installing a generator, <strong>consult a licensed electrician/contractor</strong> and your utility to confirm sizing,
      transfer equipment, interconnection rules, and code compliance.
    </p>
